"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkorion_belt_docs=globalThis.webpackChunkorion_belt_docs||[]).push([[48130],{77735(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"orion-belt-vs-teleport","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/orion-belt-vs-teleport","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-07-16-orion-belt-vs-teleport.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-07-16-orion-belt-vs-teleport.md","title":"Orion Belt vs Teleport \u2014 a practical Teleport alternative for SSH PAM","description":"Compare Orion Belt and Teleport for self-hosted privileged access. When a lighter SSH bastion/PAM gateway wins, when Teleport\u2019s broader platform is worth it, plus Boundary and classic bastions.","date":"2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"},{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"},{"inline":false,"label":"Teleport","permalink":"/blog/tags/teleport","description":"Comparisons and alternatives"},{"inline":false,"label":"Self-hosted","permalink":"/blog/tags/self-hosted","description":"Running infrastructure yourself"}],"readingTime":3.45,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"orion-belt-vs-teleport","title":"Orion Belt vs Teleport \u2014 a practical Teleport alternative for SSH PAM","description":"Compare Orion Belt and Teleport for self-hosted privileged access. When a lighter SSH bastion/PAM gateway wins, when Teleport\u2019s broader platform is worth it, plus Boundary and classic bastions.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["ssh","pam","teleport","self-hosted"],"keywords":["Teleport alternative","Orion Belt vs Teleport","open source PAM","self-hosted SSH bastion","Boundary vs bastion"]},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Orion Belt v1.0 \u2014 self-hosted SSH PAM gateway is stable","permalink":"/blog/welcome-orion-belt-v1"}},"content":"**Short version:** Orion Belt is a self-hosted **SSH access gateway with PAM workflows**. Teleport is a **broad zero-trust access platform**. If you mainly need mediated SSH, recording, JIT, and MFA \u2014 without inbound ports on every host or a large ops surface \u2014 Orion Belt is the lighter **Teleport alternative**.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nThis comparison is for practitioners evaluating **open source PAM** / **self-hosted privileged access** options for SSH, not a dunk contest. Licensing differs; verify current Teleport terms for your use case. Orion Belt is Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause ([details](/blog/commons-clause-honesty)).\\n\\n## Who should read this\\n\\n- Teams searching for a **Teleport alternative** focused on SSH  \\n- Homelab and SMB operators who find Teleport\u2019s surface area large  \\n- Security engineers comparing bastion vs platform approaches  \\n\\n## Side-by-side\\n\\n| Dimension | Orion Belt | Teleport | HashiCorp Boundary | Traditional bastion |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Primary job | SSH PAM / bastion gateway | Multi-protocol zero-trust access | Identity-aware session brokering | Network jump point |\\n| Protocols (typical) | SSH / SCP (focused) | SSH, K8s, DB, web, Windows, \u2026 | Many via targets/workers | Whatever you tunnel |\\n| How targets are reached | **Agents dial out** (reverse SSH) | Node agents / tunnels / IoT | Workers / proxies | Inbound to bastion; often inbound to hosts |\\n| Inbound on targets | Not required for agent path | Depends on mode | Depends on layout | Common |\\n| Session recording | Yes (+ live watch) | Yes | Yes (with recording path) | DIY |\\n| JIT / approvals | Built-in (+ ChatOps) | Access requests / roles | Via IdP / workflows | Rare |\\n| MFA | TOTP + WebAuthn; FIDO SSH keys | Strong IdP / MFA story | Via IdP | DIY |\\n| Authorization | ReBAC (+ optional OpenFGA) | RBAC / roles / traits | IAM-centric | OS users / keys |\\n| SSH CA | Optional built-in | First-class cert story | Different model | Manual / none |\\n| Ops weight | Smaller SSH-focused deploy | Larger platform | Medium\u2013large | Small but feature-poor |\\n| Hosting | Self-hosted | Self-hosted or cloud | Self-hosted or HCP | Self-hosted |\\n\\n## Architecture contrast\\n\\n### Traditional bastion\\n\\n```text\\nOperator \u2192 (SSH) \u2192 Bastion \u2192 (SSH) \u2192 Target\\n```\\n\\nYou still manage keys, often lack recording/JIT, and frequently still expose SSH somewhere on the path.\\n\\n### Orion Belt\\n\\n```text\\nOperator \u2192 Gateway \u2190 (reverse SSH) \u2190 Agent on target\\n```\\n\\nThe target initiates the tunnel. The gateway brokers sessions, enforces policy, and can record or live-watch. Background: [Why reverse SSH agents](/blog/why-reverse-ssh-agents).\\n\\n### Teleport-shaped platforms\\n\\nPowerful and broad: many protocols, deep identity integration, large feature surface \u2014 and correspondingly more to deploy, learn, and operate.\\n\\n## When to choose Orion Belt\\n\\nChoose Orion Belt if most of these are true:\\n\\n- Privileged access is **mostly SSH**  \\n- You want **no inbound SSH** on application hosts  \\n- You want **recording + live watch + JIT** without a PAM appliance  \\n- You prefer **self-hosted**, Linux-first, inspectable code  \\n- You accept a **narrower scope** today (OIDC, HA, other protocols on the roadmap)\\n\\nHands-on: [Try in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes).\\n\\n## When Teleport (or similar) is a better fit\\n\\nChoose Teleport if you need:\\n\\n- First-class **Kubernetes / DB / Windows / web** access in one product now  \\n- A large ecosystem and org-wide zero-trust program already centered on that tool  \\n- Features Orion Belt has not shipped yet  \\n\\n## When Boundary fits better\\n\\nBoundary shines when the center of gravity is **identity + credential brokering** in a HashiCorp world \u2014 not \u201cSSH bastion with PAM workflows\u201d as the primary UX.\\n\\n## Security tradeoffs (reverse agents)\\n\\n**Gain:** targets need outbound reachability to the gateway, not inbound SSH from attackers\u2019 scan range.  \\n**Cost:** offline agents are unreachable; the gateway is a high-value control plane \u2014 harden it, encrypt recordings, require MFA for admins.\\n\\n## SEO-style FAQ\\n\\n**Is Orion Belt a Teleport alternative?**  \\nFor SSH-centric self-hosted PAM/bastion needs, yes. For full multi-protocol zero trust, Teleport remains broader.\\n\\n**Is Orion Belt open source?**  \\nSource-available under Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause \u2014 free to self-host; not for sale as a product/SaaS wrapper. Not OSI \u201cOpen Source\u201d in the strict sense.\\n\\n**Can I migrate from a jump host?**  \\nYes: enroll agents, move humans to `user+host@gateway`, turn on recording, then tighten inbound SSH. See [bastion vs PAM](/blog/bastion-vs-pam).\\n\\n## Try before you debate\\n\\n```bash\\ngit clone https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt.git\\ncd orion-belt\\n./scripts/docker-quickstart.sh\\n```\\n\\n[Documentation](/docs/introduction) \xb7 [GitHub](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt) \xb7 [Discord](https://discord.gg/w62S8jxTHJ)"},{"id":"welcome-orion-belt-v1","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/welcome-orion-belt-v1","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-07-16-welcome-orion-belt-v1.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-07-16-welcome-orion-belt-v1.md","title":"Orion Belt v1.0 \u2014 self-hosted SSH PAM gateway is stable","description":"Orion Belt v1.0 is released \u2014 self-hosted SSH access gateway with reverse agents, session recording, JIT, MFA, and ReBAC. Try the 10-minute path and join early operators.","date":"2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"},{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"},{"inline":false,"label":"Self-hosted","permalink":"/blog/tags/self-hosted","description":"Running infrastructure yourself"}],"readingTime":1.48,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"welcome-orion-belt-v1","title":"Orion Belt v1.0 \u2014 self-hosted SSH PAM gateway is stable","description":"Orion Belt v1.0 is released \u2014 self-hosted SSH access gateway with reverse agents, session recording, JIT, MFA, and ReBAC. Try the 10-minute path and join early operators.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["ssh","pam","self-hosted"],"keywords":["Orion Belt v1","self-hosted PAM","SSH bastion release","Teleport alternative"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Orion Belt vs Teleport \u2014 a practical Teleport alternative for SSH PAM","permalink":"/blog/orion-belt-vs-teleport"},"nextItem":{"title":"Join Orion Belt early operators \u2014 first self-hosted SSH PAM deployments","permalink":"/blog/looking-for-early-operators"}},"content":"**Orion Belt v1.0** is out: a stable, self-hosted **SSH access gateway with PAM workflows**. Reverse agents, session recording, live watch, JIT approvals, MFA/WebAuthn, ReBAC, optional SSH CA, Linux packages, and a web console \u2014 without a SaaS dependency.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nThis is the release note for operators who have been waiting for a version line we are willing to call production-shaped for the SSH slice.\\n\\n## What \u201cv1.0\u201d means here\\n\\n- SSH proxy / bastion path we will not casually break  \\n- Documented Docker quickstart and package installs  \\n- Recording + live watch on the gateway path  \\n- JIT + ChatOps approvals  \\n- MFA options for the console  \\n- ReBAC (optional OpenFGA)  \\n- Optional SSH CA  \\n- OpenAPI + observability docs in the main repo  \\n\\nStill on the roadmap (not pretend-done): OIDC, HA, additional protocols. Honesty > checkbox theater \u2014 [lessons](/blog/lessons-building-self-hosted-pam).\\n\\n## Positioning\\n\\nTeleport-like SSH access control \u2014 **without** opening inbound ports on every host or adopting a large platform.\\n\\nCompare: [Orion Belt vs Teleport](/blog/orion-belt-vs-teleport). Landscape: [open-source PAM guide](/blog/open-source-pam-landscape).\\n\\n## Try it in about ten minutes\\n\\n```bash\\ngit clone https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt.git\\ncd orion-belt\\n./scripts/docker-quickstart.sh\\n```\\n\\nThen: [Try Orion Belt in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes) through agent \u2192 SSH \u2192 Sessions playback.\\n\\n## License\\n\\nApache 2.0 + Commons Clause \u2014 free to self-host and use internally; you cannot sell Orion Belt as a product or substantially derived hosted service. [Plain-language FAQ](/blog/commons-clause-honesty).\\n\\n## Join early operators\\n\\nWe want deployments and sharp feedback more than vanity metrics. [Early operators call](/blog/looking-for-early-operators) \xb7 [Discord](https://discord.gg/w62S8jxTHJ) \xb7 [Discussions](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt/discussions)\\n\\n## Links\\n\\n- [orion-belt.dev](https://orion-belt.dev)  \\n- [GitHub](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt)  \\n- [Documentation](/docs/introduction)"},{"id":"looking-for-early-operators","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/looking-for-early-operators","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-07-08-looking-for-early-operators.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-07-08-looking-for-early-operators.md","title":"Join Orion Belt early operators \u2014 first self-hosted SSH PAM deployments","description":"We are looking for the first ~20 teams and labs running Orion Belt v1.0. Get install help, influence the roadmap, and help shape a self-hosted Teleport alternative for SSH.","date":"2026-07-08T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"Self-hosted","permalink":"/blog/tags/self-hosted","description":"Running infrastructure yourself"},{"inline":false,"label":"Ops","permalink":"/blog/tags/ops","description":"Deploying and running Orion Belt"},{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"}],"readingTime":1.47,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"looking-for-early-operators","title":"Join Orion Belt early operators \u2014 first self-hosted SSH PAM deployments","description":"We are looking for the first ~20 teams and labs running Orion Belt v1.0. Get install help, influence the roadmap, and help shape a self-hosted Teleport alternative for SSH.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["self-hosted","ops","pam"],"keywords":["self-hosted PAM community","SSH bastion early access","Orion Belt operators"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Orion Belt v1.0 \u2014 self-hosted SSH PAM gateway is stable","permalink":"/blog/welcome-orion-belt-v1"},"nextItem":{"title":"Lessons learned building a self-hosted SSH PAM gateway","permalink":"/blog/lessons-building-self-hosted-pam"}},"content":"GitHub stars are a lagging indicator. The leading indicator we care about is simple: **are serious people deploying Orion Belt and telling us what breaks?**\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nThis is an open call for **early operators** \u2014 roughly the first twenty labs or small teams running v1.0 as a real **self-hosted SSH PAM / bastion** path.\\n\\n## Who we want\\n\\n- Homelab / self-hosting users with more than one Linux box  \\n- Small company SRE/DevOps teams needing recording + JIT without SaaS  \\n- Security engineers evaluating a **Teleport alternative** for SSH-only scope  \\n- People willing to file reproducible bugs (Docker quickstart welcome)\\n\\n## Who we are not optimizing for (yet)\\n\\n- Enterprises needing HA + OIDC + multi-protocol on day one  \\n- Teams blocked by Commons Clause / non-OSI policy ([license notes](/blog/commons-clause-honesty))  \\n- Drive-by \u201cplease add my niche protocol\u201d without deploying SSH first  \\n\\n## What you get\\n\\n- Direct help on [Discord](https://discord.gg/w62S8jxTHJ) when agents will not dial out  \\n- Faster eyes on your issues and PRs  \\n- Input on roadmap sequencing (OIDC, HA, etc.)  \\n- Optional public credit as an early operator  \\n\\n## What we ask\\n\\n1. Complete [Try in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes)  \\n2. Leave it running on something you actually use (even a homelab VM)  \\n3. Open GitHub issues with versions, logs, and repro steps  \\n4. Tell us if docs lied  \\n\\n## How to raise your hand\\n\\n- Message in Discord  \\n- Open a [GitHub Discussion](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt/discussions)  \\n- Or comment on an issue that you are running v1.0 in anger  \\n\\nMetrics we track privately for the first month: install attempts, active deployments, external issues \u2014 not vanity follower counts. Background: [lessons building PAM](/blog/lessons-building-self-hosted-pam).\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [v1.0 announcement](/blog/welcome-orion-belt-v1)  \\n- [Why reverse SSH agents](/blog/why-reverse-ssh-agents)"},{"id":"lessons-building-self-hosted-pam","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/lessons-building-self-hosted-pam","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-06-26-lessons-building-self-hosted-pam.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-06-26-lessons-building-self-hosted-pam.md","title":"Lessons learned building a self-hosted SSH PAM gateway","description":"Practical lessons from building Orion Belt \u2014 access control vs audit, UX for JIT, reverse tunnel tradeoffs, licensing honesty, and keeping a 10-minute install path sacred.","date":"2026-06-26T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"},{"inline":false,"label":"Architecture","permalink":"/blog/tags/architecture","description":"Design and tradeoffs"},{"inline":false,"label":"Ops","permalink":"/blog/tags/ops","description":"Deploying and running Orion Belt"}],"readingTime":1.85,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"lessons-building-self-hosted-pam","title":"Lessons learned building a self-hosted SSH PAM gateway","description":"Practical lessons from building Orion Belt \u2014 access control vs audit, UX for JIT, reverse tunnel tradeoffs, licensing honesty, and keeping a 10-minute install path sacred.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["pam","architecture","ops"],"keywords":["self-hosted PAM","building SSH bastion","privileged access lessons","open source PAM"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Join Orion Belt early operators \u2014 first self-hosted SSH PAM deployments","permalink":"/blog/looking-for-early-operators"},"nextItem":{"title":"Shipping deb/rpm/apk packages and a Docker lab for SSH PAM","permalink":"/blog/linux-packages-and-labs"}},"content":"Orion Belt v1.0 is our line in the sand for a stable **self-hosted SSH PAM** slice. These are the lessons that shaped it \u2014 useful if you are building similar infrastructure or evaluating whether our tradeoffs match yours.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n## 1. Access control is easy compared to audit\\n\\nReBAC graphs are approachable. Faithful, replayable, retainable **session recordings** are not. Budget engineering time accordingly. Deep dive: [Session recording is hard](/blog/session-recording-is-hard).\\n\\n## 2. UX beats feature count for JIT\\n\\nIf temporary access takes longer than sharing a key, standing keys win. ChatOps approvals and a short CLI/UI path matter more than a twelfth policy DSL. See [JIT access](/blog/jit-access-approvals).\\n\\n## 3. Reverse tunnels move risk; they don\u2019t delete it\\n\\nAgents dialing out remove inbound SSH on targets and concentrate trust on the gateway. Harden the gateway like a directory service. Explained in [Why reverse SSH agents](/blog/why-reverse-ssh-agents).\\n\\n## 4. Optional complexity must stay optional\\n\\nSSH CA, OpenFGA, and WebAuthn are valuable. None of them should block the first recorded session. Optional flags exist so labs stay fast ([SSH CA](/blog/optional-ssh-ca), [MFA](/blog/mfa-webauthn-ssh)).\\n\\n## 5. License clarity is a security feature\\n\\nPeople evaluating PAM software are professionally paranoid. Commons Clause disclosed early builds trust even when it loses some adopters. [License FAQ](/blog/commons-clause-honesty).\\n\\n## 6. Protect the 10-minute path like an API\\n\\nEvery feature PR should ask: did we break `docker-quickstart` \u2192 agent \u2192 Sessions? If yes, fix or document before merge. [Install path design](/blog/ten-minute-install-path).\\n\\n## 7. Say no to protocol sprawl in v1\\n\\nKubernetes and database proxies are real needs. Shipping a mediocre version of each would dilute the SSH promise. Roadmap honesty > checkbox theater. Comparison mindset: [vs Teleport](/blog/orion-belt-vs-teleport).\\n\\n## 8. Dual packaging is worth it\\n\\nDocker converts; packages retain. [Packages and labs](/blog/linux-packages-and-labs).\\n\\n## What we want next from the community\\n\\nSharp issues from people who **deployed** something \u2014 not drive-by feature wishes. If that is you: [early operators](/blog/looking-for-early-operators).\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [Announcing Orion Belt](/blog/announcing-orion-belt)  \\n- [Discord](https://discord.gg/w62S8jxTHJ) \xb7 [GitHub](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt)"},{"id":"linux-packages-and-labs","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/linux-packages-and-labs","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-06-12-linux-packages-and-labs.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-06-12-linux-packages-and-labs.md","title":"Shipping deb/rpm/apk packages and a Docker lab for SSH PAM","description":"Why Orion Belt ships native Linux packages and a Docker quickstart \u2014 two audiences for self-hosted SSH bastion installs, signed repos, and reproducible bug reports.","date":"2026-06-12T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"Ops","permalink":"/blog/tags/ops","description":"Deploying and running Orion Belt"},{"inline":false,"label":"Self-hosted","permalink":"/blog/tags/self-hosted","description":"Running infrastructure yourself"},{"inline":true,"label":"linux","permalink":"/blog/tags/linux"}],"readingTime":1.66,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"linux-packages-and-labs","title":"Shipping deb/rpm/apk packages and a Docker lab for SSH PAM","description":"Why Orion Belt ships native Linux packages and a Docker quickstart \u2014 two audiences for self-hosted SSH bastion installs, signed repos, and reproducible bug reports.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["ops","self-hosted","linux"],"keywords":["SSH bastion packages","self-hosted PAM Docker","deb rpm apk","Linux privileged access"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Lessons learned building a self-hosted SSH PAM gateway","permalink":"/blog/lessons-building-self-hosted-pam"},"nextItem":{"title":"SSH bastion host vs PAM gateway \u2014 which problem are you solving?","permalink":"/blog/bastion-vs-pam"}},"content":"Real gateways want **systemd** and signed package repos. First-time evaluators want `docker compose` and a browser. Orion Belt ships both on purpose. This post explains the split for operators installing a **self-hosted SSH bastion / PAM** stack.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n## Two audiences, two artifacts\\n\\n| Audience | Success looks like | Artifact |\\n| --- | --- | --- |\\n| Security / platform eng | Survives reboot, upgrades, SELinux | deb / rpm / apk + docs |\\n| Curious SRE on a laptop | Recorded session in 10 minutes | `docker-quickstart.sh` |\\n\\nIf you only ship packages, blog traffic bounces. If you only ship Docker, production teams bounce. Document them as **siblings**, not one confused path \u2014 see [10-minute install path](/blog/ten-minute-install-path).\\n\\n## What \u201cmake packages\u201d is for\\n\\nFrom the product repo:\\n\\n```bash\\nmake packages\\n# optional signed repos with ORION_REQUIRE_SIGN=1\\n```\\n\\nYou get installable **server**, **agent**, and **tools** packages for common Linux distros. First-run after packages: server YAML, `setup`, Add agent \u2014 covered in [Server setup](/docs/quickstart/server) and the main repo `SETUP.md` / `PACKAGING.md`.\\n\\n## What Docker is for\\n\\n- Marketing conversion  \\n- Reproducing GitHub issues  \\n- Homelabs and CI smoke tests  \\n- Demoing reverse agents without cloud VMs  \\n\\nWhen someone says \u201cagent won\u2019t connect,\u201d asking for a Docker quickstart repro saves days of \u201cwhat\u2019s in your custom unit file?\u201d\\n\\n## Signed repos and supply chain\\n\\nGPG-signed APT/RPM trees matter once you leave the lab. Treat packaging keys like release keys: generate, backup, publish the public key, and document fingerprint verification. The scripts in-tree (`gen-packaging-key.sh`, `publish-repos.sh`) exist so you are not inventing that ceremony under pressure.\\n\\n## FAQ\\n\\n**Can I run production on Docker Compose?**  \\nYou can. Many teams still prefer packages + systemd for host networking and upgrade habits. Compose is not immoral; just own backup/restore for volumes.\\n\\n**Do agents need the same package format as the server?**  \\nMatch the target OS. The UI install script path is built around that.\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [Try in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes)  \\n- [Lessons building PAM](/blog/lessons-building-self-hosted-pam)  \\n- [GitHub](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt)"},{"id":"bastion-vs-pam","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/bastion-vs-pam","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-05-29-bastion-vs-pam.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-29-bastion-vs-pam.md","title":"SSH bastion host vs PAM gateway \u2014 which problem are you solving?","description":"Clarify bastion hosts versus privileged access management (PAM) for SSH. When a jump box is enough, when you need recording and JIT, and where Orion Belt fits.","date":"2026-05-29T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"},{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"},{"inline":false,"label":"Architecture","permalink":"/blog/tags/architecture","description":"Design and tradeoffs"}],"readingTime":1.53,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"bastion-vs-pam","title":"SSH bastion host vs PAM gateway \u2014 which problem are you solving?","description":"Clarify bastion hosts versus privileged access management (PAM) for SSH. When a jump box is enough, when you need recording and JIT, and where Orion Belt fits.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["ssh","pam","architecture"],"keywords":["SSH bastion host","PAM vs bastion","privileged access management SSH","self-hosted bastion"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Shipping deb/rpm/apk packages and a Docker lab for SSH PAM","permalink":"/blog/linux-packages-and-labs"},"nextItem":{"title":"Live SSH session watch for self-hosted PAM gateways","permalink":"/blog/live-session-watch"}},"content":"Engineers say \u201cbastion\u201d to mean three different products. That ambiguity wastes evaluation time. This article separates **SSH bastion hosts** from **PAM gateways**, and places Orion Belt on that map.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n## Definitions that help\\n\\n### Jump host / classic bastion\\n\\nA hardened server you SSH into, then pivot to internal hosts. Network rendezvous. Policy and audit are usually DIY.\\n\\n### SSH access gateway / recording bastion\\n\\nA control plane that brokers SSH, often with session recording and centralized authn. May use reverse tunnels or agents.\\n\\n### Privileged access management (PAM)\\n\\nA broader discipline: joiner-mover-leaver, credential vaults, password rotation, multi-protocol privileged sessions, tickets, and compliance reports. SSH is one slice.\\n\\n## Decision table\\n\\n| Need | Jump host | SSH gateway | Full PAM suite |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Reach internal SSH | \u2713 | \u2713 | \u2713 |\\n| Per-machine grants | \u2717 / DIY | \u2713 | \u2713 |\\n| Session recording | \u2717 / DIY | \u2713 | \u2713 |\\n| JIT approvals | \u2717 | \u2713 / varies | \u2713 |\\n| K8s/DB/Windows too | \u2717 | \u2717 / limited | \u2713 |\\n| Lowest ops cost | \u2713 | Medium | High |\\n\\n## Where Orion Belt fits\\n\\nOrion Belt is a **self-hosted SSH PAM gateway** (bastion + PAM workflows for SSH):\\n\\n- Reverse agents (dial out)  \\n- Recording + live watch  \\n- JIT + MFA + ReBAC  \\n- Not a full multi-protocol PAM suite in v1  \\n\\nIf your RFP says \u201cPAM\u201d but the checklist is SSH + audit + approvals, a focused gateway may close the RFP without a platform migration. If the checklist includes password checkout for Windows and database proxying next quarter, shortlist broader tools \u2014 see [open-source PAM landscape](/blog/open-source-pam-landscape) and [vs Teleport](/blog/orion-belt-vs-teleport).\\n\\n## Migration pattern we see\\n\\n1. Today: jump host + VPN  \\n2. Pain: audits, shared keys, inbound SSH  \\n3. Next: SSH gateway with recording (Orion Belt class)  \\n4. Later: expand protocols or IdP integration as needed (OIDC on our roadmap)\\n\\nDo not buy step 4 on day one unless step 4\u2019s problems are already on fire.\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [Why reverse SSH agents](/blog/why-reverse-ssh-agents)  \\n- [Announcing Orion Belt](/blog/announcing-orion-belt)"},{"id":"live-session-watch","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/live-session-watch","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-05-14-live-session-watch.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-14-live-session-watch.md","title":"Live SSH session watch for self-hosted PAM gateways","description":"How live session watch works on an SSH bastion, privacy and permission concerns, and how Orion Belt lets admins observe active privileged sessions safely.","date":"2026-05-14T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"},{"inline":false,"label":"Security","permalink":"/blog/tags/security","description":"Threat model and hardening"},{"inline":false,"label":"Ops","permalink":"/blog/tags/ops","description":"Deploying and running Orion Belt"}],"readingTime":1.6,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"live-session-watch","title":"Live SSH session watch for self-hosted PAM gateways","description":"How live session watch works on an SSH bastion, privacy and permission concerns, and how Orion Belt lets admins observe active privileged sessions safely.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["ssh","security","ops"],"keywords":["live SSH session","session monitoring","privileged session watch","SSH bastion audit"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"SSH bastion host vs PAM gateway \u2014 which problem are you solving?","permalink":"/blog/bastion-vs-pam"},"nextItem":{"title":"Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause \u2014 what Orion Belt\u2019s license means","permalink":"/blog/commons-clause-honesty"}},"content":"Sometimes playback tomorrow is too late. **Live session watch** lets an authorized admin observe an active SSH (or web terminal) session as it happens \u2014 useful for incident response, mentoring, and verifying break-glass work.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nUsed badly, it becomes silent surveillance. Used well, it is a sharp tool in a **self-hosted PAM** gateway. Here is how we think about it in Orion Belt.\\n\\n## Recording vs live watch\\n\\n| | Session recording | Live watch |\\n| --- | --- | --- |\\n| Timing | Persisted cast for later | Streaming view of an active session |\\n| Primary use | Compliance, forensics | Real-time oversight |\\n| Failure mode | Disk secrets / retention | Privacy / overreach |\\n\\nBoth sit on the **gateway path**. Direct-to-host SSH remains invisible. Cultural rule still applies: [session recording is hard](/blog/session-recording-is-hard).\\n\\n## Product requirements we care about\\n\\n1. **Explicit action** \u2014 an admin opens watch; it is not ambient for every operator  \\n2. **Authorization** \u2014 not every user role can watch every session  \\n3. **Honest lifecycle** \u2014 when the session ends, watch ends  \\n4. **Same trust boundary** as recording \u2014 if you can watch, you are already in the sensitive-data club  \\n\\n## When to use it\\n\\n- On-call verifying a risky production change  \\n- Approver stays online during a JIT window ([JIT access](/blog/jit-access-approvals))  \\n- Training: senior watches junior on a staging host  \\n- Suspected account misuse (with clear policy)\\n\\n## When not to use it\\n\\n- Routine browsing of everyone\u2019s terminals \u201cbecause we can\u201d  \\n- Legal environments without disclosed monitoring policy  \\n- As a substitute for proper pairing tools when the goal is collaboration, not control  \\n\\n## Operator tips\\n\\n- Prefer watching **JIT sessions** you already approved  \\n- Prefer staging for training watches  \\n- Assume anything typed can be seen \u2014 same as recording  \\n- Combine with ChatOps approvals so the human story is in one timeline  \\n\\nTry it after a lab SSH in [Try in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes) \u2014 open **Sessions** while the session is still active.\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [Sessions guide](/docs/guides/sessions)  \\n- [Security FAQ](/docs/faq/security)"},{"id":"commons-clause-honesty","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/commons-clause-honesty","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-04-30-commons-clause-honesty.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-04-30-commons-clause-honesty.md","title":"Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause \u2014 what Orion Belt\u2019s license means","description":"Clear explanation of Orion Belt\u2019s Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause license for self-hosted PAM \u2014 what you can do, what you cannot sell, and why we disclose it on HN and Reddit.","date":"2026-04-30T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"Self-hosted","permalink":"/blog/tags/self-hosted","description":"Running infrastructure yourself"},{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"}],"readingTime":1.82,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"commons-clause-honesty","title":"Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause \u2014 what Orion Belt\u2019s license means","description":"Clear explanation of Orion Belt\u2019s Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause license for self-hosted PAM \u2014 what you can do, what you cannot sell, and why we disclose it on HN and Reddit.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["self-hosted","pam"],"keywords":["Commons Clause","Apache 2.0 PAM","open source license self-hosted","Orion Belt license"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Live SSH session watch for self-hosted PAM gateways","permalink":"/blog/live-session-watch"},"nextItem":{"title":"Optional SSH certificate authority for self-hosted bastions","permalink":"/blog/optional-ssh-ca"}},"content":"Security infrastructure requires trust. Burying a restrictive clause until after launch is how open-source communities learn to ignore you. Orion Belt uses **Apache License 2.0 with the Commons Clause**, and we say so in the README, website, and launch posts.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nThis article is the plain-language license FAQ for people evaluating Orion Belt as **self-hosted privileged access** software.\\n\\n## What you can do\\n\\nUnder Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause (as we ship it):\\n\\n- Use Orion Belt internally, including for commercial companies  \\n- Modify the code  \\n- Self-host for your team / customers\u2019 *infrastructure you operate as part of your own business* (you are not selling Orion as the product)  \\n- Read and audit the source  \\n\\n## What you cannot do\\n\\nThe Commons Clause withholds the right to **Sell** the software. In practice for Orion Belt:\\n\\n- You may not sell Orion Belt as a product  \\n- You may not offer a hosted service whose value derives substantially from Orion Belt as the product you are selling  \\n\\nIf you want to build a managed Orion SaaS as your business, that is exactly what the clause is designed to stop without permission.\\n\\n## Is it \u201cOpen Source\u201d?\\n\\n**OSI \u201cOpen Source\u201d** has a specific meaning. Commons Clause software is often called **source-available**. We do not pretend otherwise on Hacker News, Lobsters, or Reddit.\\n\\nIf your organization requires OSI-approved licenses only, Orion Belt may be disallowed \u2014 better to know before you invest evaluation time.\\n\\n## Why not AGPL or a pure Apache 2.0?\\n\\nDifferent projects pick different weapons. Our goals:\\n\\n1. Keep the code auditable for security buyers  \\n2. Allow free self-hosting for real users  \\n3. Prevent a cloud vendor from wrapping the repo as their PAM SaaS without a deal  \\n\\nWhether you agree with that tradeoff is personal. We would rather be declined honestly than adopted under false premises.\\n\\n## How we talk about it in public\\n\\nLaunch checklist for maintainers:\\n\\n- One sentence in Show HN / Reddit  \\n- Link to LICENSE  \\n- No \u201cfully open source\u201d claims without qualification  \\n\\nFull legal text: [LICENSE](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt/blob/master/LICENSE) \xb7 [commonsclause.com](https://commonsclause.com/)\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [Announcing Orion Belt](/blog/announcing-orion-belt)  \\n- [Open-source PAM landscape](/blog/open-source-pam-landscape)"},{"id":"optional-ssh-ca","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/optional-ssh-ca","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-04-15-optional-ssh-ca.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-04-15-optional-ssh-ca.md","title":"Optional SSH certificate authority for self-hosted bastions","description":"When to enable an SSH CA in a PAM gateway, how short-lived certificates reduce key sprawl, and why Orion Belt keeps SSH CA optional for labs.","date":"2026-04-15T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"},{"inline":false,"label":"Security","permalink":"/blog/tags/security","description":"Threat model and hardening"},{"inline":false,"label":"Architecture","permalink":"/blog/tags/architecture","description":"Design and tradeoffs"}],"readingTime":1.69,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"optional-ssh-ca","title":"Optional SSH certificate authority for self-hosted bastions","description":"When to enable an SSH CA in a PAM gateway, how short-lived certificates reduce key sprawl, and why Orion Belt keeps SSH CA optional for labs.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["ssh","security","architecture"],"keywords":["SSH CA","SSH certificates","self-hosted bastion","privileged access certificates"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause \u2014 what Orion Belt\u2019s license means","permalink":"/blog/commons-clause-honesty"},"nextItem":{"title":"MFA and WebAuthn for a self-hosted SSH PAM console","permalink":"/blog/mfa-webauthn-ssh"}},"content":"Long-lived `authorized_keys` entries are how SSH access rots. An **SSH certificate authority (CA)** issues short-lived user and host certificates instead. Powerful \u2014 and easy to force on users before they have a working bastion.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nOrion Belt treats SSH CA as **optional**. You can run reverse agents, recording, JIT, and MFA without it. This article explains when to turn CA on for a **self-hosted SSH PAM** deployment.\\n\\n## What an SSH CA changes\\n\\n| Without CA | With CA |\\n| --- | --- |\\n| Standing user keys on many systems | Short-lived user certs from the gateway |\\n| TOFU / known_hosts drift | Host certificates for gateway/agents |\\n| Revocation by hunting files | Wait for expiry (+ revoke CA-side as designed) |\\n\\nOpenSSH has supported certificates for years; PAM/bastion products wrap the operational bits humans forget.\\n\\n## Why optional?\\n\\nBecause the **10-minute path** should not require understanding certificate principals, `AuthorizedPrincipalsFile`, and CA key ceremonies. Labs need wow-first. CA is a production maturity step \u2014 see [Designing a 10-minute install path](/blog/ten-minute-install-path).\\n\\n## When you should enable it\\n\\nEnable SSH CA when:\\n\\n- Key inventory is already painful  \\n- Contractors come and go weekly  \\n- You want host identity pinned via Host CA  \\n- Someone on the team can own CA key backup / rotation  \\n\\nKeep it off when:\\n\\n- You are still validating reverse agents and recording  \\n- Nobody owns secret management for the CA master key  \\n\\nOrion encrypts CA material at rest when enabled (`ssh_ca.master_key` style config in the main repo). Do not use example secrets.\\n\\n## Operational checklist\\n\\n1. Backup the CA master key like a root of trust  \\n2. Set host principals to the DNS/IPs clients actually use  \\n3. Document how agents receive host certs on enrollment  \\n4. Monitor expiry and clock skew (certs are time-sensitive)  \\n5. Pair with recording \u2014 certificates are not an audit trail  \\n\\nFull reference: [SSH_CA.md](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt/blob/master/docs/SSH_CA.md) in the product repo.\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [MFA and WebAuthn](/blog/mfa-webauthn-ssh)  \\n- [ReBAC for SSH machines](/blog/rebac-for-ssh-machines)  \\n- [Security best practices](/docs/guides/security)"},{"id":"mfa-webauthn-ssh","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/mfa-webauthn-ssh","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-03-28-mfa-webauthn-ssh.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-28-mfa-webauthn-ssh.md","title":"MFA and WebAuthn for a self-hosted SSH PAM console","description":"How Orion Belt splits console MFA (TOTP, WebAuthn) from SSH public keys and FIDO sk- keys \u2014 configuration pitfalls, rp_id origins, and practical hardening.","date":"2026-03-28T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"Security","permalink":"/blog/tags/security","description":"Threat model and hardening"},{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"},{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"}],"readingTime":1.9,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"mfa-webauthn-ssh","title":"MFA and WebAuthn for a self-hosted SSH PAM console","description":"How Orion Belt splits console MFA (TOTP, WebAuthn) from SSH public keys and FIDO sk- keys \u2014 configuration pitfalls, rp_id origins, and practical hardening.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["security","ssh","pam"],"keywords":["WebAuthn SSH","MFA privileged access","YubiKey PAM","self-hosted MFA"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Optional SSH certificate authority for self-hosted bastions","permalink":"/blog/optional-ssh-ca"},"nextItem":{"title":"How we designed a 10-minute SSH PAM install path","permalink":"/blog/ten-minute-install-path"}},"content":"Operators will reject MFA that fights SSH muscle memory. Orion Belt splits the problem: **protect the web console** with TOTP and WebAuthn, and keep **SSH on keys** \u2014 including FIDO `sk-*` keys \u2014 that OpenSSH already understands.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nIf you are hardening a **self-hosted privileged access** gateway, this is the MFA model to expect and the footguns to avoid.\\n\\n## Two planes of authentication\\n\\n| Plane | Mechanisms | Goal |\\n| --- | --- | --- |\\n| Web console `/ui` | SSH pubkey login, password+TOTP, WebAuthn | Protect admin/approver UX |\\n| SSH to gateway | Registered user keys, optional FIDO SSH keys | Day-to-day access |\\n\\nConfusing these planes creates tickets like \u201cmy YubiKey works in the browser but not in SSH\u201d \u2014 different protocols, different registration paths.\\n\\n## Console MFA\\n\\n### TOTP\\n\\nFamiliar authenticator-app second factor. Useful when hardware keys are unavailable.\\n\\n### WebAuthn / FIDO2\\n\\nBrowser security keys bound to:\\n\\n- **`rp_id`** \u2014 hostname only (e.g. `orion.example.com` or `localhost`)  \\n- **`origins`** \u2014 full origins the UI is served from (`https://orion.example.com`, maybe a Vite dev origin)\\n\\nIf `rp_id` / origins disagree with the URL in the address bar, registration and login fail in opaque ways. Fix config before blaming the YubiKey.\\n\\nDocker env knobs include `ORION_WEBAUTHN_ENABLED`, `ORION_PUBLIC_HOST`, and `ORION_PUBLIC_ORIGIN` \u2014 see `.env.server.example` in the repo.\\n\\n## SSH keys and FIDO\\n\\nUsers register SSH **public** keys on their Orion identity. OpenSSH then connects as:\\n\\n```bash\\nssh -i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519 -p 2222 alice+web-01@gateway\\n```\\n\\nFor hardware-backed SSH keys (`sk-ssh-ed25519@openssh.com`, etc.), register the public key the same way and touch the device when OpenSSH prompts. Details: main repo `docs/openssh-clients.md`.\\n\\n## Recommended hardening ladder\\n\\n1. Lab: pubkey admin via quickstart  \\n2. Staging: enable TOTP for admins  \\n3. Production: WebAuthn for admins/approvers + network allowlist on UI  \\n4. Require MFA for sensitive console actions as your threat model demands  \\n\\nAlso encrypt session recordings \u2014 MFA does not help if casts sit plaintext on disk ([session recording](/blog/session-recording-is-hard)).\\n\\n## FAQ\\n\\n**Can I force MFA on every SSH connection?**  \\nSSH MFA UX varies; many teams prefer strong keys + gateway policy + recorded sessions. Console MFA is the high-ROI control for approvals and replay.\\n\\n**Does WebAuthn replace SSH keys?**  \\nNo. It protects browser sessions to the control plane.\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [Security guide](/docs/guides/security)  \\n- [Optional SSH CA](/blog/optional-ssh-ca)  \\n- [Try in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes)"},{"id":"ten-minute-install-path","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/ten-minute-install-path","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-03-12-ten-minute-install-path.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-12-ten-minute-install-path.md","title":"How we designed a 10-minute SSH PAM install path","description":"Why Orion Belt optimizes for docker-quickstart \u2192 agent dial-out \u2192 recorded SSH. Building a conversion-friendly self-hosted bastion onboarding experience.","date":"2026-03-12T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"Ops","permalink":"/blog/tags/ops","description":"Deploying and running Orion Belt"},{"inline":false,"label":"Self-hosted","permalink":"/blog/tags/self-hosted","description":"Running infrastructure yourself"},{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"}],"readingTime":1.85,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"ten-minute-install-path","title":"How we designed a 10-minute SSH PAM install path","description":"Why Orion Belt optimizes for docker-quickstart \u2192 agent dial-out \u2192 recorded SSH. Building a conversion-friendly self-hosted bastion onboarding experience.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["ops","self-hosted","ssh"],"keywords":["self-hosted SSH bastion","Docker PAM","quickstart","Orion Belt install"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"MFA and WebAuthn for a self-hosted SSH PAM console","permalink":"/blog/mfa-webauthn-ssh"},"nextItem":{"title":"Open-source PAM and SSH bastion options compared","permalink":"/blog/open-source-pam-landscape"}},"content":"Most infrastructure products document *everything*. Conversion dies on page one. For Orion Belt, the path we care about is short on purpose:\\n\\n**gateway up \u2192 agent dials out \u2192 SSH works \u2192 session recorded \u2192 wow**\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nThis post explains why that sequence matters for a **self-hosted SSH bastion / PAM** product, what we automated in `docker-quickstart.sh`, and what we deliberately left for production docs.\\n\\n## The funnel that actually matters\\n\\nStars and HN traffic are useless if the README dumps people into YAML archaeology. Security tools especially need a **trusted first success**: if the demo lies, nobody will harden a real deployment.\\n\\nWe optimize for:\\n\\n1. Clone the repo  \\n2. One script starts Postgres + gateway + admin bootstrap  \\n3. Browser login with an SSH public key  \\n4. **Add agent** \u2192 outbound connect  \\n5. Open a session \u2192 see it under **Sessions**\\n\\nGuide: [Try Orion Belt in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes).\\n\\n## What the quickstart script does\\n\\n`./scripts/docker-quickstart.sh`:\\n\\n- Writes `.env.server` with random Postgres password + JWT secret if missing  \\n- `docker compose up` for the server stack  \\n- Waits for `/health`  \\n- Generates an admin ed25519 keypair if needed  \\n- Runs `setup` to create the first admin  \\n\\nThere is **no** self-service signup form. That is intentional: the control plane is SSH-key identity, not a random password form on the internet.\\n\\n## Why Docker for labs and packages for prod\\n\\n| Audience | Path |\\n| --- | --- |\\n| Evaluator / bug repro | Docker quickstart + compose agent |\\n| Homelab lasting a weekend | Docker or packages |\\n| Company gateway | deb/rpm/apk + hardening docs |\\n\\nBoth are real. Collapsing them into one doc produces a bad lab *and* a bad production guide. See [Linux packages and labs](/blog/linux-packages-and-labs).\\n\\n## Friction we refuse to ship in the first ten minutes\\n\\n- Manual SQL  \\n- Hand-editing JWT secrets without a generator  \\n- Requiring a public DNS name before hello-world  \\n- Forcing SSH CA on  \\n\\nThose belong *after* the wow.\\n\\n## Measure the path\\n\\nIf you fork or contribute, break the 10-minute path on purpose and see what fails. Every failure mode should either be fixed or documented in the troubleshooting table \u2014 not discovered on HN launch day.\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [Why reverse SSH agents](/blog/why-reverse-ssh-agents)  \\n- [Server setup](/docs/quickstart/server)  \\n- [GitHub](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt)"},{"id":"open-source-pam-landscape","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/open-source-pam-landscape","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-02-26-open-source-pam-landscape.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-02-26-open-source-pam-landscape.md","title":"Open-source PAM and SSH bastion options compared","description":"A practical guide to open-source privileged access and SSH bastions \u2014 Teleport, Boundary, Warpgate, DIY jump hosts, and Orion Belt as a self-hosted SSH-focused PAM gateway.","date":"2026-02-26T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"},{"inline":false,"label":"Teleport","permalink":"/blog/tags/teleport","description":"Comparisons and alternatives"},{"inline":false,"label":"Self-hosted","permalink":"/blog/tags/self-hosted","description":"Running infrastructure yourself"},{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"}],"readingTime":2.29,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"open-source-pam-landscape","title":"Open-source PAM and SSH bastion options compared","description":"A practical guide to open-source privileged access and SSH bastions \u2014 Teleport, Boundary, Warpgate, DIY jump hosts, and Orion Belt as a self-hosted SSH-focused PAM gateway.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["pam","teleport","self-hosted","ssh"],"keywords":["open source PAM","Teleport alternative","SSH bastion","self-hosted privileged access","Warpgate","Boundary"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"How we designed a 10-minute SSH PAM install path","permalink":"/blog/ten-minute-install-path"},"nextItem":{"title":"Just-in-time (JIT) SSH access with approvals that people will use","permalink":"/blog/jit-access-approvals"}},"content":"Search for **open source PAM** or **Teleport alternative** and you will find overlapping tools that solve different jobs. This guide maps the landscape for SSH-first teams: what each category is good at, where it gets heavy, and where **Orion Belt** fits as a **self-hosted SSH bastion / PAM gateway**.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n## Categories that get conflated\\n\\n### 1. Jump hosts / classic bastions\\n\\nA hardened box you SSH into, then hop onward. Cheap to start. Weak on recording, JIT, and per-machine policy unless you invent them.\\n\\n### 2. SSH gateways / recording proxies\\n\\nTools that terminate or broker SSH and may record sessions (Warpgate-like products, custom `sshd` ForceCommand setups, etc.). Stronger audit story; feature depth varies.\\n\\n### 3. Identity-centric brokers\\n\\nHashiCorp **Boundary** emphasizes identity and credential brokering in a Hashi ecosystem. Excellent if that is already your center of gravity; different UX if you mainly wanted an SSH bastion.\\n\\n### 4. Broad zero-trust platforms\\n\\n**Teleport** (and similar) cover SSH plus Kubernetes, databases, web apps, Windows, and a large policy surface. Ideal when you need that breadth; heavy when you only needed SSH PAM.\\n\\n### 5. Commercial PAM appliances\\n\\nCyberArk / BeyondTrust class: deep enterprise workflows, price and complexity to match.\\n\\n## Comparison table\\n\\n| Option | Best at | Watch-outs |\\n| --- | --- | --- |\\n| DIY jump host | Tiny labs | No JIT/recording by default |\\n| Warpgate-style gateway | Simple shared SSH gateway | PAM workflows may be thinner |\\n| Boundary | Identity + Hashi stack | Not \u201cSSH bastion UX\u201d first |\\n| Teleport | Multi-protocol zero trust | Ops and learning curve |\\n| Orion Belt | Self-hosted **SSH PAM** slice, reverse agents | Narrower protocol scope in v1 |\\n| Commercial PAM | Enterprise process depth | Cost, lock-in |\\n\\n## Where Orion Belt sits\\n\\nOrion Belt optimizes for:\\n\\n- **Self-hosted privileged access** focused on SSH/SCP  \\n- **Agents dial out** (no inbound SSH required on targets)  \\n- Session **recording + live watch**  \\n- **JIT approvals** (+ ChatOps)  \\n- MFA / WebAuthn, ReBAC, optional SSH CA  \\n- Linux packages + Docker quickstart  \\n\\nIt is intentionally a **lighter Teleport alternative** for teams whose privileged access problem is mostly SSH \u2014 not a claim to replace every Teleport protocol.\\n\\nDeep dive: [Orion Belt vs Teleport](/blog/orion-belt-vs-teleport). Architecture: [Why reverse SSH agents](/blog/why-reverse-ssh-agents).\\n\\n## How to choose in one meeting\\n\\nAsk:\\n\\n1. Do we need **non-SSH protocols** this quarter?  \\n2. Must targets stay **free of inbound SSH**?  \\n3. Is **session recording** a hard requirement?  \\n4. Do we need **JIT approvals** or is standing access OK?  \\n5. Can we run a gateway (Postgres, backups) ourselves?  \\n6. Does license policy allow **Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause**?\\n\\nIf answers skew toward SSH + self-host + recording/JIT, evaluate Orion Belt hands-on:\\n\\n[Try in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes)\\n\\n## Related reading\\n\\n- [Announcing Orion Belt](/blog/announcing-orion-belt)  \\n- [Bastion vs PAM](/blog/bastion-vs-pam)  \\n- [Commons Clause honesty](/blog/commons-clause-honesty)"},{"id":"jit-access-approvals","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/jit-access-approvals","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-02-12-jit-access-approvals.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-02-12-jit-access-approvals.md","title":"Just-in-time (JIT) SSH access with approvals that people will use","description":"How to design JIT privileged access for SSH \u2014 request, approve, expire \u2014 with ChatOps and session recording. Orion Belt\u2019s approach to temporary access workflows.","date":"2026-02-12T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"},{"inline":false,"label":"Ops","permalink":"/blog/tags/ops","description":"Deploying and running Orion Belt"},{"inline":false,"label":"Security","permalink":"/blog/tags/security","description":"Threat model and hardening"}],"readingTime":2.43,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"jit-access-approvals","title":"Just-in-time (JIT) SSH access with approvals that people will use","description":"How to design JIT privileged access for SSH \u2014 request, approve, expire \u2014 with ChatOps and session recording. Orion Belt\u2019s approach to temporary access workflows.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["pam","ops","security"],"keywords":["JIT access","temporary privileged access","SSH approval workflow","self-hosted PAM"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Open-source PAM and SSH bastion options compared","permalink":"/blog/open-source-pam-landscape"},"nextItem":{"title":"Relationship-based access control (ReBAC) for SSH machines","permalink":"/blog/rebac-for-ssh-machines"}},"content":"Standing SSH privileges are convenient until an ex-contractor key still works on Friday night. **Just-in-time (JIT) access** \u2014 request, approve, expire \u2014 is the standard answer in privileged access management. It only works if the workflow is faster than pasting a key into Slack.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nThis article covers how JIT fits a **self-hosted SSH PAM** gateway, what UX details matter, and how Orion Belt implements temporary access without making on-call hate you.\\n\\n## Why standing access fails\\n\\n- Keys outlive tickets  \\n- \u201cEmergency\u201d grants become permanent  \\n- Audit asks \u201cwho had root last month?\u201d and the answer is \u201ceveryone in `#ops`\u201d  \\n- Compliance frameworks increasingly expect **time-bound** privileged sessions  \\n\\nCommercial PAM vendors built empires on this pain. Open-source and self-hosted teams still under-serve it.\\n\\n## Anatomy of a usable JIT flow\\n\\nA flow people will follow:\\n\\n1. Engineer needs `web-01` for 90 minutes  \\n2. They submit a **reason + duration** (CLI or UI)  \\n3. Approver gets a ping (console bell and/or ChatOps)  \\n4. Approval creates a grant that **auto-expires**  \\n5. Session is **recorded** while they work  \\n6. Grant disappears; recording remains for review  \\n\\nA flow people will bypass:\\n\\n1. Open four tabs of wiki  \\n2. File a ticket in a system nobody watches at 2am  \\n3. Wait for a manager who is asleep  \\n4. \u2026so they reuse yesterday\u2019s shared key  \\n\\n## Orion Belt\u2019s building blocks\\n\\n- **Access requests** with reason and duration  \\n- **Approvals** in the web console  \\n- **ChatOps plugins** for Slack, Discord, Teams, Rocket.Chat \u2014 approvals where the team already lives  \\n- **Recording + live watch** on the gateway path  \\n- ReBAC grants underneath (see [ReBAC for SSH machines](/blog/rebac-for-ssh-machines))  \\n\\nExample CLI shape:\\n\\n```bash\\nosh web-01 --request-access --duration 1h --reason \\"Incident 4821 rollback\\"\\n```\\n\\n## ChatOps without turning chat into your IdP\\n\\nChat approvals are great for speed. They are not a substitute for:\\n\\n- Authenticating the approver properly  \\n- Logging who approved what  \\n- Ensuring the bot cannot be spoofed casually  \\n\\nKeep ChatOps as a **notification + action surface** bound back to the gateway\u2019s authz, not a free-for-all emoji vote.\\n\\n## Pair JIT with recording\\n\\nTemporary access without audit just **delays** standing privilege. The conversion story we optimize for in docs is:\\n\\nrequest \u2192 approve \u2192 SSH \u2192 **Sessions playback**\\n\\nLab walkthrough: [Try in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes).\\n\\n## Policy ideas you can copy\\n\\n| Scenario | Duration | Approver | Remote user |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| On-call break-glass | 1\u20132h | Another on-call / lead | root |\\n| Deploy to one app host | 30\u201360m | Service owner | deploy |\\n| Vendor debug | 2\u20134h | Security + owner | restricted user |\\n| Homelab tinkering | 24h | You | whatever you use |\\n\\n## FAQ\\n\\n**Does JIT replace MFA?**  \\nNo. MFA protects the console / identity; JIT limits *when* privileged relationships exist.\\n\\n**What if the approver is offline?**  \\nDefine a backup approver rotation. A JIT system with one human bottleneck will be routed around.\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [Session recording is hard](/blog/session-recording-is-hard)  \\n- [Looking for early operators](/blog/looking-for-early-operators)  \\n- [Discord](https://discord.gg/w62S8jxTHJ)"},{"id":"rebac-for-ssh-machines","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/rebac-for-ssh-machines","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-01-28-rebac-for-ssh-machines.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-01-28-rebac-for-ssh-machines.md","title":"Relationship-based access control (ReBAC) for SSH machines","description":"How ReBAC maps users to SSH machines and remote users in a self-hosted PAM gateway, when to use OpenFGA, and how Orion Belt keeps grants practical.","date":"2026-01-28T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"},{"inline":false,"label":"Architecture","permalink":"/blog/tags/architecture","description":"Design and tradeoffs"},{"inline":false,"label":"Security","permalink":"/blog/tags/security","description":"Threat model and hardening"}],"readingTime":2.51,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"rebac-for-ssh-machines","title":"Relationship-based access control (ReBAC) for SSH machines","description":"How ReBAC maps users to SSH machines and remote users in a self-hosted PAM gateway, when to use OpenFGA, and how Orion Belt keeps grants practical.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["pam","architecture","security"],"keywords":["ReBAC SSH","OpenFGA","privileged access","self-hosted PAM","SSH authorization"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Just-in-time (JIT) SSH access with approvals that people will use","permalink":"/blog/jit-access-approvals"},"nextItem":{"title":"Why SSH session recording is harder than access control","permalink":"/blog/session-recording-is-hard"}},"content":"Most SSH fleets still authorize with a pile of `authorized_keys` files and a spreadsheet nobody updates. **Relationship-based access control (ReBAC)** is a clearer model for a **self-hosted PAM** gateway: users have relationships to machines (and to remote OS users), not a single \u201cops can root everywhere\u201d bit.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nThis guide explains how ReBAC shows up in Orion Belt, how it differs from coarse RBAC, and when optional **OpenFGA** is worth introducing.\\n\\n## RBAC vs ReBAC in one paragraph\\n\\n**RBAC** says: Alice has role `sre`, and role `sre` may access production.  \\n**ReBAC** says: Alice is `can_access` on machine `web-01` as remote user `deploy` \u2014 a direct relationship in a graph.\\n\\nRBAC scales via roles; ReBAC scales via relationships. SSH privileged access is naturally relational: *person \u2194 machine \u2194 unix account \u2194 time window*.\\n\\n## How Orion Belt models it\\n\\nAt a practical level:\\n\\n1. **Users** authenticate with SSH public keys (plus optional MFA on the console).  \\n2. **Agents / machines** enroll with the gateway.  \\n3. **Grants** attach a user to a machine with allowed **remote users** (`root`, `ubuntu`, `deploy`, \u2026).  \\n4. JIT requests create **time-bounded** relationships instead of standing grants.\\n\\nUI surfaces: **Users**, **Permissions**, **Agents**. CLI examples live in [User management](/docs/guides/user-management) and the server setup docs.\\n\\n```bash\\norion-belt-server permission grant \\\\\\n  --user alice --machine web-01 --type both --remote-users deploy\\n```\\n\\n## Remote users are still Linux users\\n\\nReBAC does not invent OS accounts. If you grant `alice \u2192 web-01 as root`, the `root` account must exist on the agent host. Orion brokers the session; the agent host still enforces local account reality.\\n\\nThis is intentional. A PAM gateway should not pretend to replace `/etc/passwd`.\\n\\n## Optional OpenFGA\\n\\nSome organizations already run [OpenFGA](https://openfga.dev/) (or similar) as a central authorization service. Orion Belt can optionally delegate authorization checks there instead of only using built-in tables.\\n\\n**Use built-in ReBAC when:**\\n\\n- You want the smallest self-hosted footprint  \\n- Your grant graph is \u201cusers \u2194 machines\u201d  \\n\\n**Consider OpenFGA when:**\\n\\n- Authorization is already centralized for other apps  \\n- You need richer tuple models shared outside SSH  \\n\\nMisconfiguring external authz is a footgun \u2014 fail closed, and test grants in a lab first.\\n\\n## Least privilege patterns that work\\n\\n1. **Default deny** \u2014 no grant, no SSH through the gateway.  \\n2. **Per-machine grants** instead of \u201cproduction\u201d mega-roles when possible.  \\n3. **Non-root remote users** for day-to-day work; root via JIT.  \\n4. **Separate auditor identities** for session playback.  \\n5. **Revoke on offboarding** as a checklist item next to GitHub org removal.\\n\\n## FAQ\\n\\n**Is this Zanzibar?**  \\nReBAC as a family includes Zanzibar-style systems. Orion\u2019s built-in path is the pragmatic SSH subset; OpenFGA is the escape hatch for fuller models.\\n\\n**Can groups map to many machines?**  \\nUse tags/metadata for organization, but remember: **tags are not grants**. Access still needs an explicit permission edge (or a higher-level automation that creates those edges).\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [JIT SSH access](/blog/jit-access-approvals)  \\n- [Machine management](/docs/guides/machine-management)  \\n- [Orion Belt vs Teleport](/blog/orion-belt-vs-teleport)"},{"id":"session-recording-is-hard","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/session-recording-is-hard","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2026-01-09-session-recording-is-hard.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-01-09-session-recording-is-hard.md","title":"Why SSH session recording is harder than access control","description":"Building reliable SSH session recording for a self-hosted PAM gateway \u2014 PTY quirks, secret leakage, retention, encryption, and live watch. How Orion Belt approaches auditability.","date":"2026-01-09T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"},{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"},{"inline":false,"label":"Security","permalink":"/blog/tags/security","description":"Threat model and hardening"}],"readingTime":3.02,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"session-recording-is-hard","title":"Why SSH session recording is harder than access control","description":"Building reliable SSH session recording for a self-hosted PAM gateway \u2014 PTY quirks, secret leakage, retention, encryption, and live watch. How Orion Belt approaches auditability.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["ssh","pam","security"],"keywords":["SSH session recording","privileged access audit","self-hosted PAM","SSH bastion recording"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Relationship-based access control (ReBAC) for SSH machines","permalink":"/blog/rebac-for-ssh-machines"},"nextItem":{"title":"Announcing Orion Belt \u2014 open-source self-hosted SSH PAM / bastion","permalink":"/blog/announcing-orion-belt"}},"content":"Granting \u201calice may SSH to `web-01`\u201d is the easy half of privileged access. The hard half is answering, months later: **what exactly happened in that shell?** Access control is a graph. **SSH session recording** is a stream of messy terminal I/O, storage policy, and human behavior.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nThis article is for operators evaluating **self-hosted PAM** or an **SSH bastion** with audit requirements \u2014 SOC-minded startups, regulated teams, and homelabs that still want a paper trail.\\n\\n## Access control vs auditability\\n\\n| Concern | Typical difficulty | Failure mode |\\n| --- | --- | --- |\\n| Authn (keys, MFA) | Medium | Stolen key, weak MFA |\\n| Authz (who \u2192 which host) | Medium | Over-broad roles |\\n| **Recording** | High | Gaps, unreadable casts, secret sprawl on disk |\\n| Live watch | High | Latency, privacy, \u201cwho can watch whom\u201d |\\n\\nMany DIY bastions stop after authz. Then an incident arrives and nobody can replay the session that mattered.\\n\\n## Why terminal recording is messy\\n\\n### PTYs are not logs\\n\\nInteractive SSH is a pseudo-terminal: resize events, ANSI color, cursor motion, binary-ish output from `top` or `vim`. A naive \u201clog stdout\u201d approach produces files humans cannot replay. Orion Belt uses cast-style recordings suitable for console playback \u2014 the same family of ideas behind asciinema-like players.\\n\\n### Secrets show up in cleartext\\n\\nPeople paste API tokens into shells. Recordings then become **secret stores**. Treat recording storage like a vault:\\n\\n- Encrypt at rest when possible (`recording.encryption_key` in Orion)  \\n- Restrict who can open **Sessions** in the UI  \\n- Set **retention** deliberately  \\n- Train operators not to paste production secrets into recorded sessions (or use short-lived creds)\\n\\n### Completeness depends on the path\\n\\nIf a user SSHs **directly** to the agent host, the gateway never sees the session. Recording is not magic \u2014 it only covers traffic that traverses the gateway. The operational rule has to be cultural and technical: **gateway or it didn\u2019t happen.**\\n\\n## What \u201cgood\u201d looks like in a PAM gateway\\n\\nFor Orion Belt\u2019s v1 SSH slice we care about:\\n\\n1. **Record by default** on the Docker / recommended path  \\n2. **Playback** in the web console (seek / pause)  \\n3. **Live watch** for active sessions when an admin needs eyes-on  \\n4. **Compression + retention** knobs for disk reality  \\n5. Optional **encryption at rest**\\n\\nWeb terminal sessions are first-class too (`source=web`) \u2014 not only CLI SSH.\\n\\n## Live watch vs recording\\n\\n| | Recording | Live watch |\\n| --- | --- | --- |\\n| When | After / during flush | During active session |\\n| Use | Incident review, compliance | Pairing, suspicious activity |\\n| Risk | Secrets on disk | Privacy / over-surveillance |\\n\\nBoth should be **permissioned**. Silent always-on screen sharing for every admin is how you lose trust inside the company.\\n\\nDeep dive: [Live session watch](/blog/live-session-watch).\\n\\n## Implementation checklist for self-hosted teams\\n\\nBefore you call your **SSH bastion** \u201cauditable\u201d:\\n\\n1. Force human SSH through the gateway (OpenSSH `user+host@gw` or `osh`)  \\n2. Enable recording; set retention days you can defend  \\n3. Turn on encryption at rest for anything beyond a lab  \\n4. Limit replay roles (auditor vs operator)  \\n5. Test a full loop: connect \u2192 type \u2192 disconnect \u2192 playback  \\n\\nLab path: [Try in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes) ends on the Sessions page for a reason \u2014 that is the conversion moment.\\n\\n## FAQ\\n\\n**Are recordings a substitute for shell history?**  \\nNo. Histories are per-user, incomplete, and editable. Gateway recordings are a different control.\\n\\n**Can I disable recording?**  \\nYes in config \u2014 not recommended if you claimed PAM-style audit to leadership.\\n\\n**Where are files stored?**  \\nDefault `/var/lib/orion-belt/recordings` (or the Docker volume). Plan disk like you plan log volume.\\n\\n## Related\\n\\n- [Why reverse SSH agents](/blog/why-reverse-ssh-agents)  \\n- [JIT access approvals](/blog/jit-access-approvals)  \\n- [Sessions guide](/docs/guides/sessions)  \\n- [GitHub](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt)"},{"id":"announcing-orion-belt","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/announcing-orion-belt","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2025-12-18-announcing-orion-belt.md","source":"@site/blog/2025-12-18-announcing-orion-belt.md","title":"Announcing Orion Belt \u2014 open-source self-hosted SSH PAM / bastion","description":"Orion Belt is a self-hosted SSH access gateway with PAM workflows \u2014 reverse agents, session recording, JIT approvals, MFA, and ReBAC. A lighter Teleport alternative for SSH-first teams.","date":"2025-12-18T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"},{"inline":false,"label":"PAM","permalink":"/blog/tags/pam","description":"Privileged access management"},{"inline":false,"label":"Self-hosted","permalink":"/blog/tags/self-hosted","description":"Running infrastructure yourself"}],"readingTime":2.56,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"announcing-orion-belt","title":"Announcing Orion Belt \u2014 open-source self-hosted SSH PAM / bastion","description":"Orion Belt is a self-hosted SSH access gateway with PAM workflows \u2014 reverse agents, session recording, JIT approvals, MFA, and ReBAC. A lighter Teleport alternative for SSH-first teams.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["ssh","pam","self-hosted"],"keywords":["open source PAM","SSH bastion","self-hosted privileged access","Teleport alternative"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Why SSH session recording is harder than access control","permalink":"/blog/session-recording-is-hard"},"nextItem":{"title":"Why reverse SSH agents beat opening inbound ports on every server","permalink":"/blog/why-reverse-ssh-agents"}},"content":"**Orion Belt** is an open-source, **self-hosted SSH access gateway** with PAM-style workflows. It sits in the gap between a raw jump host and a full zero-trust platform: reverse agents, session recording, live watch, JIT approvals, MFA/WebAuthn, ReBAC, and an optional SSH CA \u2014 without SaaS dependency.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nThis post is the product introduction for operators evaluating an **open source PAM** option focused on SSH, or a practical **Teleport alternative** when you do not need every protocol on day one.\\n\\n## Who this is for\\n\\n- DevOps / SRE / Linux admins managing fleets over SSH  \\n- Homelab and **self-hosted** users who want audit trails without a vendor cloud  \\n- Small companies that need **privileged access** controls but not a CyberArk deployment  \\n- Teams tired of inbound `:22` on every box \u201cjust for the bastion\u201d\\n\\n## The problem we kept hitting\\n\\nTraditional SSH access fails in predictable ways:\\n\\n- Long-lived keys copied into chat  \\n- No native approval workflow for break-glass  \\n- Spotty or nonexistent session recording  \\n- Broad VPN access instead of per-machine grants  \\n- \u201cEnterprise PAM\u201d locked behind proprietary licensing and SaaS\\n\\nCommercial products and large open platforms solve real problems \u2014 and often arrive with an ops surface larger than the SSH problem you actually have.\\n\\n## What Orion Belt is (and is not)\\n\\n### It is\\n\\nA **Linux-first SSH/SCP bastion gateway** you run yourself:\\n\\n| Capability | Role |\\n| --- | --- |\\n| Reverse agents | Targets dial **out** \u2014 no inbound hole required on the host for Orion |\\n| Gateway | Brokers sessions, enforces ReBAC, records traffic |\\n| JIT access | Request \u2192 approve \u2192 expire (UI / API / ChatOps) |\\n| MFA | TOTP + WebAuthn for the console; FIDO SSH keys supported |\\n| Clients | `osh` / `ocp` / `oadmin`, vanilla OpenSSH, or web terminal |\\n| Packaging | Docker quickstart, deb/rpm/apk |\\n\\n### It is not\\n\\n- A multi-protocol mesh for Kubernetes, Windows RDP, and databases on day one (roadmap items exist; SSH is the v1 promise)  \\n- A hosted SaaS (by design)  \\n- A drop-in replacement for every Teleport feature  \\n\\nPositioning we use deliberately: *Teleport-like SSH access control without opening inbound ports or adopting a large platform.*\\n\\n## Architecture in one diagram\\n\\n```text\\nCLI / OpenSSH / Web UI  \u2192  Gateway (:2222 SSH, :8080 UI)\\n                              \u2191 reverse SSH\\n                           Agent on target\\n```\\n\\nDetails: [Architecture overview](/docs/architecture/overview) and [Why reverse SSH agents](/blog/why-reverse-ssh-agents).\\n\\n## License \u2014 said up front\\n\\nOrion Belt ships under **Apache 2.0 + Commons Clause**:\\n\\n- Free to use, modify, and **self-host**, including internal commercial use  \\n- You **cannot sell** Orion Belt (or a hosted service whose value derives substantially from it) as a product  \\n\\nWe disclose this on community posts (HN, Lobsters, Reddit) because security software requires trust. Full text: [LICENSE](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt/blob/master/LICENSE). More context: [Commons Clause honesty](/blog/commons-clause-honesty).\\n\\n## Try it\\n\\n```bash\\ngit clone https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt.git\\ncd orion-belt\\n./scripts/docker-quickstart.sh\\n```\\n\\nWalkthrough: [Try Orion Belt in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes).\\n\\n## Links\\n\\n- Website: [orion-belt.dev](https://orion-belt.dev)  \\n- Source: [github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt)  \\n- Chat: [Discord](https://discord.gg/w62S8jxTHJ)  \\n- Compare: [Orion Belt vs Teleport](/blog/orion-belt-vs-teleport)"},{"id":"why-reverse-ssh-agents","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/why-reverse-ssh-agents","editUrl":"https://github.com/zrougamed/orion-belt-docs/edit/master/blog/2025-12-05-why-reverse-ssh-agents.md","source":"@site/blog/2025-12-05-why-reverse-ssh-agents.md","title":"Why reverse SSH agents beat opening inbound ports on every server","description":"Learn how reverse SSH tunnels work for bastion and PAM gateways, the security tradeoffs versus inbound SSH, and why Orion Belt agents dial out instead of exposing port 22.","date":"2025-12-05T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"SSH","permalink":"/blog/tags/ssh","description":"SSH access, bastions, and tunnels"},{"inline":false,"label":"Architecture","permalink":"/blog/tags/architecture","description":"Design and tradeoffs"},{"inline":false,"label":"Security","permalink":"/blog/tags/security","description":"Threat model and hardening"},{"inline":false,"label":"Self-hosted","permalink":"/blog/tags/self-hosted","description":"Running infrastructure yourself"}],"readingTime":4.6,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Orion Belt","title":"Maintainers","url":"https://orion-belt.dev","page":{"permalink":"/blog/authors/orion"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/orion-belt-dev.png","key":"orion"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"why-reverse-ssh-agents","title":"Why reverse SSH agents beat opening inbound ports on every server","description":"Learn how reverse SSH tunnels work for bastion and PAM gateways, the security tradeoffs versus inbound SSH, and why Orion Belt agents dial out instead of exposing port 22.","authors":["orion"],"tags":["ssh","architecture","security","self-hosted"],"keywords":["reverse SSH","SSH bastion","reverse tunnel","self-hosted PAM","no inbound SSH"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Announcing Orion Belt \u2014 open-source self-hosted SSH PAM / bastion","permalink":"/blog/announcing-orion-belt"}},"content":"If you run Linux servers at any scale, you already know the uncomfortable default: **someone opens SSH from somewhere**. A bastion host, a VPN, a \u201ctemporary\u201d security-group rule that outlives the outage. Traditional **SSH bastion** designs still often assume the gateway (or the operator) can reach port 22 on the target.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nOrion Belt takes a different default for its **self-hosted PAM / SSH access gateway**: agents on target machines **dial out** to the gateway over reverse SSH. Operators never need inbound SSH on the application hosts. This article explains why that model exists, how it compares to classic bastions, and which tradeoffs you should accept with eyes open.\\n\\n## The problem with inbound SSH (even \u201cjust from the bastion\u201d)\\n\\nA classic pattern looks like this:\\n\\n```text\\nOperator \u2192 Bastion \u2192 (SSH :22) \u2192 Target\\n```\\n\\nThat path creates recurring pain:\\n\\n1. **Firewall inventory grows forever** \u2014 every VPC, VLAN, and cloud account needs rules so the bastion can reach targets.\\n2. **Targets stay in the attack surface** \u2014 anything that accepts inbound SSH can be scanned, credential-stuffed, or hit by a compromised jump box.\\n3. **NAT and ephemeral environments fight you** \u2014 laptops, CI runners, and locked-down cloud subnets often cannot be \u201creached\u201d; they can only dial out.\\n4. **Audit is incomplete** \u2014 if anyone still SSHs direct to the host, your bastion\u2019s session recording never sees it.\\n\\nA **Teleport alternative** or commercial PAM product will solve pieces of this with agents, workers, or IoT tunnels. The underlying idea is the same: **move reachability so the target initiates connectivity**.\\n\\n## What \u201cagents dial out\u201d means\\n\\nIn Orion Belt:\\n\\n```text\\nOperator \u2192 Gateway (SSH :2222 / HTTPS UI)\\n                \u2191\\n         reverse SSH\\n                \u2191\\n              Agent on target\\n```\\n\\n1. You install a small **agent** on the machine you want to manage.\\n2. The agent authenticates to the **gateway** and keeps a reverse tunnel open (outbound from the target\u2019s perspective).\\n3. When an operator connects to the gateway (CLI, OpenSSH `user+machine@gateway`, or web terminal), the gateway **brokers** the session through that tunnel.\\n4. Policy (ReBAC), MFA on the console, JIT approvals, and **session recording / live watch** all sit on the gateway path.\\n\\nThe target still runs Linux users and SSH semantics for the remote account you land on (`root`, `ubuntu`, \u2026). What changes is **who is allowed to open a connection toward that host from the network**.\\n\\n## Security tradeoffs (honest)\\n\\n### Gains\\n\\n- **No inbound SSH required on targets** for the Orion path \u2014 useful for hardened subnets and \u201cdeny all ingress\u201d baselines.\\n- **One control plane** for authentication, authorization, and recording.\\n- **Works behind NAT** as long as the agent can reach the gateway on the SSH port (typically **2222**).\\n\\n### Costs\\n\\n- **Offline agent = unreachable host** until it reconnects. There is no magic wake-up if the process is dead.\\n- **The gateway becomes high-value infrastructure.** Treat it like a domain controller for SSH: patch it, restrict who can reach `:2222` / the UI, encrypt recordings, require MFA for admins.\\n- **You must trust and update the agent binary** on every enrolled machine \u2014 same class of risk as any other node agent (Teleport, monitoring, backup).\\n\\nIf your environment cannot allow **outbound** connections from targets to a central gateway, reverse agents are the wrong tool. Pick a model that matches your network policy.\\n\\n## Reverse tunnels vs VPN vs classic bastion\\n\\n| Approach | Typical exposure | Recording / JIT | Ops weight |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Direct SSH to hosts | Inbound :22 everywhere | DIY | Low features |\\n| Classic bastion | Inbound to bastion + often bastion\u2192host :22 | Rare / custom | Low\u2013medium |\\n| Full-mesh VPN | Broad L3 reachability | Separate tools | Medium |\\n| Reverse-agent gateway (Orion Belt) | Inbound mainly to gateway; agents outbound | Built-in path | Medium, SSH-focused |\\n\\nVPNs solve \u201chow do packets route.\u201d They do not automatically give you **privileged access management**: approvals, per-machine grants, or session playback. A **self-hosted privileged access** gateway sits *above* connectivity.\\n\\n## When reverse agents are the right default\\n\\nChoose this model if most of these are true:\\n\\n- Your privileged access problem is **mostly SSH**\\n- You want a **self-hosted SSH bastion** without SaaS lock-in\\n- Security wants **no inbound SSH** on app tiers\\n- You need **recording + JIT** without buying a CyberArk-class appliance\\n- You are okay operating a gateway (Postgres, backups, hardening)\\n\\nPrefer a broader platform (for example Teleport) if you need first-class Kubernetes, database, Windows, and web app access in one product on day one. See our comparison: [Orion Belt vs Teleport](/blog/orion-belt-vs-teleport).\\n\\n## Try the model in about ten minutes\\n\\nThe fastest way to feel the tradeoff is not a whitepaper:\\n\\n```bash\\ngit clone https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt.git\\ncd orion-belt\\n./scripts/docker-quickstart.sh\\n```\\n\\nThen follow [Try Orion Belt in 10 minutes](/docs/quickstart/try-in-10-minutes): register an agent, dial out, SSH through the gateway, open **Sessions** for playback.\\n\\n## FAQ\\n\\n**Is reverse SSH the same as `ssh -R`?**  \\nConceptually related: the remote side opens a channel back toward you. Orion Belt productizes that idea with enrollment, policy, and recording \u2014 not a one-off shell tunnel.\\n\\n**Do I still expose port 22 on the target?**  \\nNot for the Orion path. You may leave local SSH for break-glass; just know those sessions bypass gateway recording.\\n\\n**What about lateral movement from a compromised gateway?**  \\nA compromised gateway is bad in *any* bastion design. Mitigate with MFA, least privilege, network allowlists, recording encryption, and host hardening \u2014 see the main repo\u2019s deployment hardening docs.\\n\\n## Next reading\\n\\n- [Announcing Orion Belt](/blog/announcing-orion-belt)\\n- [Session recording is hard](/blog/session-recording-is-hard)\\n- [Architecture overview](/docs/architecture/overview)\\n- [Discord](https://discord.gg/w62S8jxTHJ) \xb7 [GitHub](https://github.com/orion-belt-dev/orion-belt)"}]}}')}}]);